tate agency or powerful individual to court might be willing to sue her insurance company if it refuses to compensate her for damages following an auto accident. Hendley finds that Russian judges pay close attention to the law in mundane disputes, which account for the vast majority of the cases brought to the Russian courts.Any reluctance on the part of ordinary Russian citizens to use the courts is driven primarily by their fear of the time and cost—measured in both financial and emotional terms—of the judicial process. Like their American counterparts, Russians grow more willing to pursue disputes as the social distance between them and their opponents increases; Russians are loath to sue friends and neighbors, but are less reluctant when it comes to strangers or acquaintances. Hendley concludes that the "rule of law" rubric is ill suited to Russia and other authoritarian polities where law matters most—but not all—of the time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCourts of first instancezRussia (Federation). 0aCourtszRussia (Federation). 0aLawxSocial aspectszRussia (Federation). 0aLawzRussia (Federation). 0aRule of lawzRussia (Federation). 4aHistory. 4aLegal History & Studies. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh  acontemporary Russia, Russian law, conflict resolution, Russian courts, Russia's new justice, judicial independence, justice law.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170810740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501708107423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501708107/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL 